Rating: 2
I've just read up this type of icing in Joy of Cooking, which calls it boiled white icing. They recommend cooking the sugar syrup first, then at the temperature where it streams off a spoon in thick threads, trickling it very slowly into the egg whites as you beat them. It says this cooks the egg whites as you beat them. I don't know whether this would be more reliable than the combined approach described in this recipe, but this version does seem to let a lot of people down.

Rating: 2
I'm only doing the frosting, as it was my daughter's wish to have a vanilla cake with peppermint frosting. I've had the same problem as many others - the frosting recipe just does not work with my equipment. After 20 minutes of hand beating over barely simmering water, I got the marshmallowy consistency. I then put it to beat on high with a hand blender, and this completely destroyed the consistency of the frosting, returning it to liquid. Attempts to revive it by hand blending have not worked. It seems a waste. I suspect there is some sort of problem with using a hand blender for this recipe - if you have a standard mixer as described by the recipe it may be the way to make it work. Leaving out the water might also help. In the meantime, I need to figure out how to turn this into a frosting in some other way. It does at least taste great, if you like the sort of peppermint patty flavour - because it's essentially just mint and sugar.

Rating: 4
excellent! if you follow some of the other suggestions. First of all be sure to use big enough pans. 9" round and definetly 2" high. The cake recipe makes lots of batter. Line with parchment and I use pam to spray. I put the layers in the fridge after the ganache and again after the white chocolate cream. I did not even bother to make the peppermint frosting and instead made a whipped cream frosting also has cream cheese and vanilla frosting. will def make again.

Rating: 4
This cake is phenomenal...especially with a few modifications. First, use parchment to line the bottom of the cake pans because the cake WILL stick if you don't. I recommend adding 1/4 cup of either oil or mayonnaise to the cake mix. It's just a little too crumbly otherwise. (Not necessarily dry; just crumbly). Refrigerate or freeze the cake before cutting it and before stacking the tiers in order to avoid crumbling. I found that the most successful way to assemble the cake without having it collapse (as it did the first time I made it) is this: apply the chocolate ganache to each of three pieces and refrigerate. Once the ganache has solidified, add the white chocolate cream. Refrigerate again for about 1-2 hours. Now you can stake all four pieces successfully. FINALLY, I recommend using a vanilla buttercream for the icing OR simply making more white chocolate cream for the icing. The marshmallow frosting takes about 4 times as long to make as the recipe indicates and it just isn't good. It's a bit of a misfit too--the rest of the cake is so rich and luxurious. The marshmallow frosting is just "blah" in comparison and detracts from the cake's grandeur.

Rating: 0
