Rating: 0
This turned out very well for me. My family loved it. I read the reviews before I did it, so I was pleasantly surprised when it came out. However, this cake is not for the novice, since it is fairly expensive to make, fairly time consuming, and if you aren't comfortable "troubleshooting" then it might completely botch. I agree with other people that the number one key to this is chilling after each new icing application. I put ganache on all three layers, chilled all three, then applied the buttercream, chilled all three, then stacked them. I then chilled the put-together cake, and made the frosting. It took me much longer than 9 minutes to get the "ribbon-creating" consistency, around 20 minutes or so. But it worked out well.

Rating: 4
HooEEY! I cheated and used a different Devil's food cake (Devil's Food Cake with Brown Sugar Buttercream) and it was fantastic! The other cake recipe would have easily made Four layers, but I thought with all the trouble people had, I'd go for a safer Three (slightly thick) as it was for Christmas. So I did the Cakes Two days ahead, and did the Ganache and White Buttercream One day ahead. There were loads of all the fillings/frostings, I think even with Four layers there would mostly be too much. Keeping the Ganache at room temp, and chilling the white chocolate mixture thoroughly before beating the cream in until stiff worked perfectly for me. I also spread Ganache and chilled each layer, before spreading cold Buttercream and chilling, before stacking the layers. I forgot to add the water to the frosting, but whipped the other ingredients to combine before continuing to whip with an electric mixer over the heat. It thickened quickly and became a perfect, stiff Marshmallow Fluff off the heat with a little more whipping. I used bamboo skewers to stabilise the cake, just in case, but they weren't necessary in the end. The frosting (which there was far too much of) went on beautifully, and I covered the sides with chocolate curls and made a ring on top with crushed candy cane. I also halved the peppermint in both applications. Everyone was thoroughly impressed, and almost sickly happy.

Rating: 2
Thank goodness for other cooks' reviews! This cake turned out fine, but with several modifications. And If I were to make it again, I would definitely do a few other things differently. THE CAKE: If you make the cake as specified, and use parchment paper on the pans and spray them well, and watch the cooking time carefully (i.e., start checking at 25 minutes), you will have a delicious, not too dry, chocolate cake that comes out of the pans with no problems. THE GANACHE: I had no problems with this as written. It was just the right amount and very delicious. THE WHITE CHOCOLATE CREAM: This is where things get a little hairy. I actually didn't make the peppermint frosting for the top and sides, and just used this cream for between layers. It is absolutely delicious, but as other reviewers have mentioned, it makes the layers slide off each other. Perhaps the white peppermint frosting could go over the ganache and on the sides of the cake, and then just make a small amount of this cream for the very top.

Rating: 4
After reading the reviews, I started way in advance and I think that is the number one tip for this recipe. Chill each frosted layer separately, and make sure the cake is completely cooled. I added a TB of mayonnaise to the cake batter and had no problems with dryness. Also used springform pans lined with parchment paper and butter/floured all; nothing stuck. I used a Cuisinart stick blender with a whisk attachment to make the peppermint frosting over the simmering pan and it worked incredibly quickly, even shorter than the suggested time in the recipe. Highly recommend it. The only issue I had was in chilling the cake since it is too large to fit in a standard cake dome and the icing got mashed into the lid. Otherwise a very satisfying recipe to create if time consuming.

Rating: 3
This is one of my favorite cakes to make around the holidays and gets lots of rave reviews from family and friends. The one and only complaint I have about this recipe (one many who have reviewed it share) is that the frosting recipe is completely inaccurate. My husband and I spent 20 minutes whisking the frosting mixture over the stove by hand (way past the recommended 8-9 minutes) to get a thick'ish marshmallow consistency. I then set the mixture in the stand mixer for 10 minutes on high. When I turned it off, it was even runnier than when I'd taken the mixture off the stove. Making this frosting either requires some sort of master culinary technique that is not known by amateur cooks, or the recipe is flat out wrong. Otherwise, the cakes, ganache, and fillings are phenomenal. Will continue to make this recipe but perhaps next time explore a different frosting option.

Rating: 4
I just had to tell how my daughter and I made this cake together for my 65th birthday. First of all it was incredibly delicious. some reviewers said the cake was crumbly and dry. so we used two devils food cake mixes, two boxes of instant devils food pudding, 8 eggs, a 16oz carton of sour cream, a cup of oil and two cups of water. we baked it in three 10 cake pans. we greased the pans with crisco and floured them and then sprayed the pans with pam. we baked at 350 for 45 minutes. when the layers were completely cool we split them in half and brushed the cut sides liberally with simple syrup. we made the chocolate ganache and white chocolate cream as directed,doubling the recipe. they turned out great and our cake layers were perfection. we spread on the chocolate ganache, the white chocolate cream until we had a 6 layer masterpiece. we inserted some very thin wooden dowels and had no slipping or sliding. we used the extra chocolate ganache and iced the sides filling in any spaces . the marshmello frosting was a complete disaster. it took over an hour of whisking over the simmering water to achieve the right consistency and then it was sugary and grainy like sand. we put two sticks of softened butter and two lbs of powerded sugar in the bowl of my stand mixer. we started mixing on low and then added two heaping spoonfuls of the white chocolate cream,about a cup and half, we turned the mixer to medium high and beat until fluffy. we frosted the cake with this delicious mint white chocolate butter cream. and oh yes, we reduced all the peppermint extract called for by half. Our cake was moist, creamy and rich with a hint of mint. hope this helps any one wanting to try the recipe. I always spray everything with pam and nothing ever sticks.

Rating: 3
This recipe is absolutely delicious, however I did experience technical difficulties consistent with those of other reviewers. I will note that I used vanilla extract in lieu of mint extract and it tasted fantastic. First, despite using non-stick tier cake pans and buttering and then flowering the pans, I did have issues with the cake sticking to the pans. Also, the cake seemed a bit on the dry side and crumbled VERY easily. I think this has much to do with the fact that the cake recipe does not include oil. The next time I try to make this, I will definitely add about 1/4 cup of oil to see if the resulting cake is more moist and less crumbly. Second, my cake collapsed after I added the fourth layer. It did not help that the bottom layers became slippery with the white chocolate cream. My recommendation would be to refrigerate between layers to allow the cream and ganache to harden more. I will definitely make this again with the modifications I suggested above. You will not be disappointed with the result, especially if you use premium ingredients, including high quality chocolates like Ghirardelli.

