The cake was delicious and the flavors were wonderfully balanced. It is not for the novice baker or someone in a rush. It was a bit like baking bread.... the total amount of active prep time wasn't huge, but you must tend to it multiple times during the course of the day. I made the recipes exactly as specified. The recipe for the cake part produced nice, even cakes that were very easy to slice into layers (something I usually have trouble with). In fact, it will be my "go-to" devil's food recipe. I made the fillings on the same day I used them, and the ganache spread just fine. I popped the cake into the fridge for 30min or so after each ganache application so had no problems with it running down the sides. The white choc filling was also easy (and not at all too peppermint-y). It shouldn't be runny-- you should whip it like you are making stiff whipped cream. Again, I chilled the cake each time after adding it. Frosting: it did take longer to 'ribbon' than the recipe said, but not much longer. It's a 7-minute frosting.... you have to work very fast, as the recipe states. If you do, it gives a beautiful, snowy frosting and the firmness allows you to 'sculpt' the edges as you work. I think it actually gives very professional looking results. I think that each component was easy and the overall key is chilling as you build the layers. The cake looked beautiful and everyone who shared it with us raved about it, so I would really encourage someone thinking of making it to go for it. I'd hate to see all these negative reviews dissuade someone from making what my friends and family thought was a fantastic celebration cake.

Rating: 3
I made this cake for the family dinner on Christmas Eve because who could resist the picture. It was in fact delicious but the recipe is not a beginner it is most certainly for an experienced baker that can troubleshoot any issue that will arise. It is next to impossible to make all of the components and assemble in the same day so my suggestion is making the cake one day and the 2 fillings the following day and assembeling. From this point it can be held in the fridge and frosted at a later moment. The cake should sit out of the fridge for a significant time to allow the dark chocolate filling time to warm a bit but ideally assemble and frost and serve all within an afternoon because the dark chocolate ganache wants to set up firm and the white chocolate creme wants to deflate and run. If you choose to make the white chocolate creme in advance be sure to whip vigorously to restiffen the whipped cream mixture or you'll be guaranteed to have a frustrating sloppy mess. The cake is delicious and it looked like I frosted a hat box before we cut it but it provided the wow factor I was hoping for.

