We ogled this beautiful cake on the cover photo - as did so many. What a shame. Bon Appettit - did you REALLY test this? Experienced Aunt and Novice Baker Niece made this on Christmas Eve. Too bad we didn't read the reviews before we made it! Frosting: face it, the frosting recipe has incorrect ingredients and/or proportions. Never quite worked, and we gave it 2 tries. Even when we managed to make a thick enough frosting, there was only enough for the top of the cake and it was too stiff to spread. (BonAppettit, care to comment?) Basic 7 min frosting would be fine. Assembly: refrigerate cake as you assemble to keep it intact! Ganache: delicious and generous, not too stiff as some found. Batter: too much for just two 9" pans. We trusted the recipe and it overflowed. Peppermint flavor: excessive but overall flavors tasted great together; candy-like and very rich. Serves at least 15-18: a little goes a long way (cut into 4ths and slice each 4th into thin horizontal slices, not wedges - looks nice too).

Rating: 0
Although it turned out just like the photo and tasted wonderful, I would not make this cake again because there are too many recipes to try and too little time. Thanks to one and all for the helpful hints. I used a good number of them and here are a few of my own for those who like to meet a challenge. To cut down on crumbs, I baked the cake in four 9" pans buttered and dusted with cocoa (a Martha Stewart trick), for a total of 18 minutes, rotating the pans from upper to lower racks and from side to side after 9 minutes. I chilled the ganache and white chocolate cream base overnight, then beat the cream filling almost to the point of butterization - no slouchy stuff here. Would make only half the ganache and thin it with cream as suggested. As everyone else did, I had to nuke it to make it spreadable - 40 seconds did the trick. Ganache all the layers before stacking. Add white chocolate cream as you stack them. Chill cake while making frosting. Place all the frosting ingredients, except the peppermint extract, in the bowl of a stand mixer and beat with a HAND mixer until well blended. Place bowl over a saucepan with about an inch of boiling water, making sure the water doesn't touch the bottom of the bowl. Beat constantly with the hand mixer for seven minutes - you should have a meringue that is between soft and stiff. Remove bowl from heat and place it on the mixer stand. Add peppermint extract and beat with whisk attachment until stiff peaks form - only a few minutes should do it. This is one recipe where a good stand mixer is worth its weight in cocoa beans.

