Rating: 3
I made this for a Christmas dinner with some girlfriends last night, and ended up with a delicious and beautiful dessert that was a hit. It was quite labor intensive though, especially as I wanted to avoid some of the pitfalls other reveiwers have come accross. I made the cake (only 3 layers, since I did not have any cake pans with 2" sides, but had 3 regular 9" pans) and the chocolate ganache the night before. I found the cake itself to be very moist and tasty. The next day I made the white chocolate cream. The ganache had to be warmed in the microwave prior to using. I spread the ganache over the two bottom layers, then put the cakes in the fridge about 10 minutes to let it set. Then I repeated the process with the chilled white chocolate cream and stacked all the layers carefully. I set 3 wooden coffee stirrers into the center to stabilize the layers, and that worked very well. I then put the whole cake back into the fridge for 3 hours. I then made the peppermint frosting, and ended up hand whipping it for about 25 minutes to get it to the marshmallow creme stage. The 10 more minutes with the mixer and the frosting easily spread and did not even try to slide down the sides of the cake. Overall I was very pleased with how the cake turned out, but cannot see myself making this very labor intensive dessert again.

